node.text:
We start our first novel study on Monday and I’m very excited!

My coworker does these mystery boxes so kids can start making inferences about the novel. I grabbed some items and put a box together for us.

A bone, a coconut, a dog, and a fish… any guesses what we’re reading? It’s an OLD one!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jill ❤️ Hello Fifth in Los Angeles, California.

node.text:
Today, I ate lunch and then tested my markers. It was incredibly relaxing. 😂

I’m not sure if this actually ranks under “self care,” but I was decidedly sad when I got to the last marker. 😉

Do you do anything during the school day to take a little break? I’d love to hear below!

node.text:
Here’s to a new week of sharp pencils, fresh starts, and rainbow organizers.

Basically all of my favorite things. 😂

Link in profile for this rainbow. It sits on my teacher table and I love it. 🌈

node.text:
I took this picture before the first day of school and I can tell because we now have anchor charts up on the math wall.

This week, we will start learning some math games and activities that are available as a may do. They’re all housed in those cubbies and I promise to share in stories as we cover them.

I’ve found that having a huge math wall in the front means that it gets used and referenced ALL day long.

Any questions? Ask below and I’ll do my best to answer! ❤️

For some it’s a review and for others it’s new. It gives us all a shared base and from there, we can really jump into mentor sentences.

I found this little lamp at Hobby Lobby and had to add it our library.

Also, the magnetic letterboard has been a hit with the kids. They like to change the wording, so I never really know what it’ll say. 😉

We just wrapped up week THREE and I am happy, exhausted, and excited. How are YOU doing??

node.text:
Last year, we had to do modified (very modified) soft starts. They couldn’t work together or collaborate or problem solve as a team.

We CAN this year and it makes me all emotional to watch them work together. We are masked and sanitized but we are working and learning and playing. In groups and teams and partnerships.

All the things I used to just DO that I now appreciate beyond measure.

Link in profile for this highly popular popper puzzle. ❤️

node.text:
The Chromebook cart is in the classroom next door so each day, my tech assistants (a class job) go and grab the amount we need. Some kids bring home devices and some use school ones.

I didn’t like them stacked so I grabbed some dish racks from the Dollar Tree. They fit the Chromebooks perfectly and keep screens from cracking.

At the end of the day, students return devices to the racks, where the tech assistants charge them in the locked cart next door.

I love an easy (and cheap!) fix! 💻

node.text:
Greek and Latin roots are in full swing and I love watching my students dive in!

We do a little bit each day, spending about 15 minutes in our language block on the root of the week.

Click the link in my profile to read a little more about how we do it and what we use!

State studies are well underway and we are already learning so much!

This Friday, we take our quiz on the Pacific region states. They have a study guide (link in profile) but we also practice throughout the day and during transitions.

Our clean up song at the end of each day is Tour the States, which we all love (and I can sing forward and backward 🤪).

node.text:
Boot camp was a HUGE success last week! I took very few photos because we were super busy BUT I’ll share how we did it.

On a Friday, we took the pre-assessment and I *did* read through them over the weekend so I’d know where we were all coming from.

On Monday, we launched the official boot camp. For us, this meant about 45 minutes of direct instruction, hands on activities, and small groups.

We covered two parts of speech each day; the anchor charts got glued into our ELA spirals so that they can be referenced later.

Each part of speech has multiple activities so I would put some on the countertop for early finishers. As students worked, I either walked around and helped or pulled a group to the rug.

On Friday, they took the final and every single student blew me away!

We are now (this week) launching mentor sentences and I’m so excited to see much they grow and develop, both with this AND as writers.

Link in profile to check it out!

This board just makes me smile every single time I glance at it!

Birthdays, self portraits, and a little bit of Yoda. 😉

The birthday frame was a @homegoods find and the portraits are on index cards.

Also, please note the triple border, which looks cute but was a nightmare to put up and I vow to never do it again. 😂
